WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:07.200
- In the criminal justice
system.

2
00:00:07.270 --> 00:00:08.570
the people are represented

3
00:00:08.670 --> 00:00:11.110
by two separate.
yet equally important groups:

4
00:00:11.170 --> 00:00:12.970
the police.
who investigate crime.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.800
and the district attorneys.
who prosecute the offenders.

6
00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:18.280
These are their stories.

7
00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:24.790
-
Help! Help!

8
00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.410
Help. someone. please.
We're trapped.

9
00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:31.290
Shh.

10
00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:41.740
- Anyone here?

11
00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:43.410
- Please. you have to help me!

12
00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:44.510
- Come on.
- Through here.

13
00:00:44.570 --> 00:00:46.070
- Shh. shh. shh.

14
00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:52.500
- Ma'am.
I need you to calm down.

15
00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:54.420
We're gonna get you out.
- Please. you have to help us!

16
00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:57.340
- I need you to stand back.

17
00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:01.960
Come on. come on. Let's go.

18
00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:03.390
We don't have much time.

19
00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:04.560
Go with them.
We'll get you out.

20
00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:07.180
- Ma'am. with me.
Let's go. Come on.

21
00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:11.100
One's coming out!

22
00:01:12.130 --> 00:01:13.860
Anybody in there?

23
00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:18.970
- Eyes down. Peralta!

24
00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:20.530
Backdraft!

25
00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.650
-

26
00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:29.140
- It was a backdraft.
You've been trained for this.

27
00:01:29.240 --> 00:01:30.520
- Sorry. Cap.

28
00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:33.360
- In this job.
there's no second chances.

29
00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:36.380
- Yes. sir.

30
00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:42.930
- Vic is Clint Braddock.
captain of this ladder company.

31
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:44.530
- I'm guessing this
is the murder weapon.

32
00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:46.990
- Halligan tool.
fireman's best friend.

33
00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:48.600
- Not today.

34
00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:49.760
You were the first
on the scene?

35
00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:51.070
- Yeah.

36
00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:52.610
Call came in a little
after midnight.

37
00:01:52.670 --> 00:01:54.280
One of the firefighters
who was staying in the house

38
00:01:54.340 --> 00:01:56.840
came down and found him dead.
called 911.

39
00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:58.450
Everyone else was
upstairs asleep.

40
00:01:58.550 --> 00:02:00.150
- You know how many people
were in the house?

41
00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:02.080
- Nine. not including
the captain.

42
00:02:02.150 --> 00:02:03.520
They're all still here.

43
00:02:03.590 --> 00:02:04.650
I've got unis taking
their statements.

44
00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:06.050
- Any signs of forced entry?

45
00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:07.690
- No. but the back door
to the kitchen

46
00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:09.930
was standing wide open
when we arrived.

47
00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:14.230
- Hey. Vince.
This is our guy. Braddock.

48
00:02:14.260 --> 00:02:16.730
He was at Ground Zero on 9/11.

49
00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:19.790
Led a team into Tower 2.

50
00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:22.600
- Man was a real-life hero.

51
00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:35.730
♪ ♪

52
00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:14.150
- We responded to a 10-75.

53
00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:15.960
That's a structural fire.

54
00:03:15.990 --> 00:03:17.290
It was an apartment building.

55
00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:18.790
Things got pretty intense.

56
00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:20.900
- And you're the one
who called 911?

57
00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:22.200
- Mm-hmm.

58
00:03:22.260 --> 00:03:24.070
- All right.
Can you tell us what happened?

59
00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:27.200
- When we got back.
everyone was pretty tired.

60
00:03:27.270 --> 00:03:29.740
And you never know when
the next call is gonna come.

61
00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:32.770
So we all went to bed.
but Captain stayed up.

62
00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:34.640
He said he had some work to do.

63
00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:36.100
- What time was that?

64
00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:40.110
- Around 10:30. maybe.

65
00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.480
But I couldn't sleep.

66
00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:44.510
My adrenaline was still
pumping from the fire.

67
00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:46.610
Anyways. around midnight.

68
00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:49.090
I heard what sounded like
shouting from downstairs.

69
00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:51.330
so I got up to see
what was going on.

70
00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.350
- You see anything
or anyone suspicious?

71
00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:55.000
- No.

72
00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:57.670
Cap wasn't in his office.

73
00:03:57.700 --> 00:04:01.700
So I came downstairs and saw
that the back door was open.

74
00:04:01.770 --> 00:04:03.310
It was freezing.

75
00:04:03.410 --> 00:04:05.340
That's when I knew
something was wrong.

76
00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:09.140
So I searched the house.

77
00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:12.240
and I found him.

78
00:04:12.310 --> 00:04:14.850
- Do you know of any problems
he was having?

79
00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:16.870
Anyone who might have
wanted to hurt him?

80
00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:18.690
- No.

81
00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.980
The man wasn't just a legend.

82
00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:23.130
He was the real deal.

83
00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:27.300
He saved my life last night.

84
00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:28.700
- I spoke to the other
eight firefighters

85
00:04:28.730 --> 00:04:30.370
who were at the station
last night.

86
00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:33.030
They all gave sworn statements
that they were asleep

87
00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:35.000
and didn't hear or see
anything unusual.

88
00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:36.440
- Unhelpful.

89
00:04:36.510 --> 00:04:38.310
- Also. the same thing
about Braddock too.

90
00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.440
Dude was a hero.
Everybody loved him.

91
00:04:40.510 --> 00:04:42.210
- Okay. extra unhelpful.
but still.

92
00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:43.910
Any one of them
could be the killer.

93
00:04:43.950 --> 00:04:45.880
- Well. theoretically.
but there's this.

94
00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:47.680
Security footage
from the back entrance

95
00:04:47.750 --> 00:04:49.910
of the station shows Braddock

96
00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:52.240
letting somebody in
at around 11:26 p.m.

97
00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:53.620
- No angle on
the person's face?

98
00:04:53.690 --> 00:04:54.720
- Uh-uh.

99
00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:56.220
And because of the hood
and the jacket.

100
00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:58.230
you can't tell if it's a man
or a woman. but check this out.

101
00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:00.800
20 minutes later.
they leave out the same door.

102
00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:04.070
Now. that's 16 minutes
before the 911 call.

103
00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.840
- So looks like Braddock
knew his killer?

104
00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:08.200
I mean. what about
the murder weapon?

105
00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:09.570
Any prints?
- Dozens.

106
00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:11.540
But they all track back
to members of Braddock's

107
00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:14.180
ladder company. which tracks.

108
00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:17.080
If you zoom in. mystery
person's wearing gloves.

109
00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.220
- So how does a guy
beloved by everybody

110
00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:21.770
end up with his head bashed in?

111
00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:23.320
- I wouldn't say everyone.

112
00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:24.950
I've been going through
his text messages.

113
00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:26.480
Looks like he was going through

114
00:05:26.550 --> 00:05:28.660
a pretty nasty split
from his wife.

115
00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.030
- Sounds promising.
- And it gets better.

116
00:05:31.090 --> 00:05:33.430
Braddock had her served
with divorce papers

117
00:05:33.460 --> 00:05:35.950
yesterday afternoon.

118
00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.490
- Our understanding
is that the two of you

119
00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:42.940
were having
some marital problems?

120
00:05:42.970 --> 00:05:44.500
- You mean he was leaving me.

121
00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:46.610
- We read his text messages.

122
00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:48.340
You seemed pretty upset.

123
00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.110
- Because I didn't
want a divorce.

124
00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:52.970
Because I loved him.

125
00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:55.020
I would never.

126
00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:58.910
♪ ♪

127
00:05:59.010 --> 00:06:01.190
I had an affair.

128
00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:03.680
It was a mistake.

129
00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:06.730
I begged him to take me back.
but he couldn't.

130
00:06:06.830 --> 00:06:11.700
I hoped that maybe
with time. but no.

131
00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:15.340
- Where were you last night
around midnight?

132
00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:18.840
- I was a mess about
the divorce papers.

133
00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:20.310
So I had a few
girlfriends over.

134
00:06:20.380 --> 00:06:21.910
We drank some wine
and watched a movie.

135
00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:23.650
- Well. we'd like to get
those friends' contacts.

136
00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:26.010
if that's all right.

137
00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:29.630
- Can you think of anyone who
had issues with your husband?

138
00:06:32.390 --> 00:06:35.490
- Well. yes. actually.

139
00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:37.790
The day before yesterday.
a man came by the house.

140
00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:39.390
I don't know what it was about.
but he and Clint

141
00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:41.890
got into a fight
on the front lawn.

142
00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:43.160
- You know who the man was?

143
00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:45.170
- No. he'd already taken off
by the time I came out.

144
00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:46.770
I asked Clint
what was going on.

145
00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:49.910
but he didn't wanna
talk about it.

146
00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:51.860
- I noticed the doorbell cam
on the way in.

147
00:06:51.890 --> 00:06:53.070
Does that work?

148
00:06:55.410 --> 00:06:58.200
- Candace Newman's friends
all back up her alibi.

149
00:06:58.240 --> 00:06:59.850
Apparently.
they watched "The Notebook."

150
00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:00.950
- Oh. God.

151
00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:02.780
So she's a glutton
for punishment.

152
00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:05.050
And what about this guy
she claims

153
00:07:05.090 --> 00:07:07.220
got into an altercation
with Braddock?

154
00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:10.580
- Yeah. I got
the footage right here.

155
00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:12.730
- Why are you here? Leave.

156
00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:14.200
- Can we hear what
they're arguing about?

157
00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:16.230
- Too far away from the camera
to make it out.

158
00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:18.330
but wait for it.

159
00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:19.900
- Our vic threw
the first punch.

160
00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:22.220
- The only punch.
Leveled the guy with one swing.

161
00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:24.060
- So maybe our mystery man

162
00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:26.210
showed up at the station
to even the score?

163
00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:28.280
- Well. I used the truck's
plates to pull the DMV records.

164
00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:30.380
Belongs to
a Steven Delvecchio. 52.

165
00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:31.750
Lives in Yonkers.

166
00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:33.550
- What's the connection
with Braddock?

167
00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:35.750
- Delvecchio was
a 30-year FDNY veteran

168
00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:38.180
assigned to Braddock's ladder
company until two months ago

169
00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:39.780
when he retired.

170
00:07:39.850 --> 00:07:41.320
- Okay.

171
00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:44.130
Well. let's find out why things
got physical between these two.

172
00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:56.300
- Theo.

173
00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.680
- Is that smoke?

174
00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:02.100
- NYPD! Is anyone in there?

175
00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:03.810
- The engine's running.
- It's not smoke.

176
00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:04.980
That's exhaust.

177
00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:09.580
Find the door opener!

178
00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.390
You got it?
- I got it. Let's go.

179
00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:20.100
- Set him down here.

180
00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:21.260
Watch his head.
- I got him.

181
00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:23.330
- All right. Hey. Steven?

182
00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:27.000
Steven.

183
00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:29.700
- Hey. we need an ambulance.
1461 Elmhurst.

184
00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:31.210
Caucasian male. unconscious.

185
00:08:31.270 --> 00:08:32.810
suspected
carbon monoxide poisoning.

186
00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:34.110
-
- Hey!

187
00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:36.210
Hey. hey. hey.
Hey. can you hear me?

188
00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:37.550
Huh?
-

189
00:08:37.650 --> 00:08:38.780
- Hey.
-

190
00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:40.240
- Steven! Steven!

191
00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:41.580
You all right?

192
00:08:41.680 --> 00:08:42.620
- I'm sorry.

193
00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:44.020
- Hey. hey. it's okay.
It's okay.

194
00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:45.520
- I'm so sorry.
- It's all right.

195
00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:46.590
All right.
stay with me. all right?

196
00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:47.890
We got you.

197
00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:50.080
- I can't live with
what I've done.

198
00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:53.020
I can't take the guilt.

199
00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:56.990
♪ ♪

200
00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:02.330
.

201
00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:04.240
- He's lucky you found him
when you did.

202
00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:05.530
- I'm not sure
he'd agree with you.

203
00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:07.340
- Right. so because this
was a suicide attempt.

204
00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:10.370
we're required to hold him for
a 72-hour observation period.

205
00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:12.010
- I get it. but we'd like
to talk to him now.

206
00:09:12.050 --> 00:09:13.380
Is he awake?

207
00:09:13.450 --> 00:09:15.520
- He is. but I'd really
rather you wait until after

208
00:09:15.550 --> 00:09:17.680
the social worker has had
a chance to assess him.

209
00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:19.190
- Yeah.
that's not gonna happen.

210
00:09:19.250 --> 00:09:21.360
- He's been through a lot today
already. and in his state--

211
00:09:21.390 --> 00:09:22.490
- Listen.
we're investigating a murder.

212
00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:24.880
so if he's coherent.
he's fair game.

213
00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:26.490
-

214
00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:28.350
- I don't understand.
Clint's dead?

215
00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:30.130
- Don't waste our time here.
Steve. man.

216
00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:31.700
Come on.
- I'm serious. I didn't know.

217
00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:33.060
- Then why did we find you
in your garage

218
00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:35.670
trying to take off for good?

219
00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:38.470
- I don't wanna talk about it.

220
00:09:38.540 --> 00:09:40.200
- You already did. Steven.
You don't remember?

221
00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:41.540
You confessed.

222
00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:42.940
You said you couldn't live
with what you had done.

223
00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:44.510
that you were sorry.

224
00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:46.510
- I was talking about
something else.

225
00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:47.970
- Yeah. sure you were.

226
00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:49.450
- We know you and
Braddock were beefing

227
00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:50.750
and that he knocked
your ass out.

228
00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:52.090
We saw the video.
So what?

229
00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:53.960
You show up the next day
to get some payback?

230
00:09:54.060 --> 00:09:55.290
- Maybe things went
a little too far.

231
00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:57.050
Maybe you swung
a little too hard.

232
00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:58.030
- You don't understand.

233
00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:00.360
Clint was one of
my best friends.

234
00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.360
We worked together
for over 25 years.

235
00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.030
- I don't know about you.

236
00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:05.870
but my best friend never
punched me in the face.

237
00:10:05.900 --> 00:10:07.170
- That's probably
because you've never

238
00:10:07.240 --> 00:10:09.900
done anything as bad as I did.

239
00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:13.440
I was having
some money troubles.

240
00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:16.340
so a buddy of mine
set me up with a doctor

241
00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:17.910
who was helping guys like me.

242
00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:20.950
guys who were at Ground Zero.
get some extra cash.

243
00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:24.050
- You worked 9/11?
- Yeah. I was with Clint.

244
00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:25.550
It was a nightmare.

245
00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:28.460
It was everything you
would imagine. but worse.

246
00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:30.290
It's why the
World Trade Center Health Fund

247
00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:32.290
covers treatment for PTSD.

248
00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:35.630
- But you didn't have PTSD.

249
00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:36.760
did you?

250
00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.840
- A few months ago. Clint
figured out what was going on.

251
00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:43.610
Out of respect
for our friendship.

252
00:10:43.670 --> 00:10:45.210
he didn't turn me in.
but I had to agree

253
00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:47.980
to stop taking the cash
and retire.

254
00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:49.940
Even worse. he said
we were done as friends.

255
00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:51.810
He didn't wanna
speak to me ever again.

256
00:10:51.910 --> 00:10:54.420
So I went over to his house
to talk it out.

257
00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:56.680
But. well.
you saw how that went.

258
